Since many metal ions could quench CDs by formation of a non-fluorescent complex, the selectivity for Fe3+ against other coexisting metal ions under the same conditions was also studied. 50 μL of BN-CDs (1 mg mL−1) was diluted to 5 mL by deionized water, then metal ions of Fe3+, Ag+, Al3+, Ba2+, Ca2+, Cu2+, Fe2+, Cd2+, Co2+, Mg2+, Mn2+, Na+, Pb2+, Sn2+, Zn2+, Hg2+ or K+ was added with a final concentration of 200 μM. For another group, the BN-CDs solution was added 200 μM Fe3+ and 200 μM coexisting metal ions. The fluorescence intensities of the above solutions were collected, and the quenching coefficients ((F0-F) / F0) were recorded. As shown in Fig. 6
                        , adding of other metal ions caused no observable changes on the fluorescence intensity of BN-CDs, while a significant fluorescence quenching was observed when Fe3+ was added into the above solutions. These results showed that the BN-CDs had a really favorable selectivity for Fe3+ against the other coexisted metal ions. It should be noted that Cu2+, Fe2+ and Pb2+ are usually the interferences for Fe3+ responsive CDs according to other reported literatures (Table 1
                        ). Especially, Fe2+ coexists with Fe3+ in most biological and environmental water samples, so the outstanding anti-interference ability of the BN-CDs will ensure the reliability for quantifying Fe3+ concentration in complex environment.
